It would seem, therefore, that some lines have dropped out, in which Callicles explains his acts. It is, however, just worthy of suggestion, that the explanation may have been given by a conversation aside, seen but unheard by the audience, who might be occupied with some by-play of Stasimus. We have heard Callicles defend himself in the first act of the play, and we do not want a reproduction of his dia- logue with Megaronides. This would present a difficulty which Plautus may have been anxious to avoid. The digging up of the treasure for the dowry is dismissed just below in one line and a half.
